{% comment %}
  * A cropped image that fills the container width using background-size: cover
  * height is defined by the optional aspect ratio.  If aspect ratio is false or nil
  * the image will use natural height and will not be cropped.

  *  img_object {object}- The Image we will use
  *  aspect_ratio {float} - The aspect ratio of the image in the format {ratio}:1

  {% render 'image-fill', img_object: section.settings.image, aspect_ratio: section.settings.aspect_ratio %}
{% endcomment %}

{%- assign default_image = 'blank.svg' | asset_url -%}
{%- assign image = img_object | default: default_image -%}
{%- assign bg_position = bg_position | default: "center-center" -%}

{%- comment -%}
  Native <img loading="lazy"> instead of the legacy
  <div class="lazyload" data-bgset> CSS-background pattern. Browser
  handles intersection natively (faster than lazysizes JS), no
  data-bgset srcset list to evaluate (4 width steps via srcset
  instead of 18). The aspect-ratio reservation on the parent
  .image__fill (padding-top) is preserved so there's no CLS;
  the inner img is positioned absolute to fill it with object-fit:
  cover, mirroring the prior background-size: cover behavior.

  bg_position param (e.g., "center-center") still honored via
  object-position so existing per-instance crops are preserved.
{%- endcomment -%}
<div class="image__fill fade-in-child"
  {% if image contains 'blank.svg' %}
    style="padding-top: {{ aspect_ratio | times: 100 }}%;
           filter: brightness(.95);"
  {% elsif aspect_ratio %}
    style="padding-top: {{ aspect_ratio | times: 100}}%;
           background-image: url('{{ image | img_url: '1x1' }}');"
  {% else %}
    style="padding-top: {{ 1 | divided_by: image.aspect_ratio | times: 100}}%;
           background-image: url('{{ image | img_url: '1x1' }}');"
  {% endif %}>
  {%- if image contains 'blank.svg' -%}
  {%- else -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Hot fix 2026-04-26: removed `background-size-cover` from the img
      class. The CSS rule `.fade-in-child .background-size-cover` sets
      opacity:0 by default and only flips to opacity:1 when lazysizes
      adds the `.lazyloaded` class. Native <img loading="lazy"> never
      gets that class, so the image stays invisible forever even after
      it loads. The class was a leftover from the old CSS-background
      pattern and isn't needed here — `object-fit:cover` is already
      applied via inline style. Issue first surfaced on homepage blog
      cards + article-page recommended-articles sidebar.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <img
      class="fade-in-child"
      srcset="{% if image.width > 360 %}{{ image | img_url: '360x' }} 360w,{% endif %}
              {% if image.width > 720 %}{{ image | img_url: '720x' }} 720w,{% endif %}
              {% if image.width > 1080 %}{{ image | img_url: '1080x' }} 1080w,{% endif %}
              {% if image.width > 1600 %}{{ image | img_url: '1600x' }} 1600w,{% endif %}
              {{ image | img_url: 'master' }} {{ image.width }}w"
      sizes="100vw"
      src="{{ image | img_url: 'master' }}"
      width="{{ image.width }}"
      height="{{ image.height }}"
      loading="lazy"
      alt="{{ image.alt | strip_html | escape }}"
      style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:{{ bg_position | replace: '-', ' ' }};">
  {%- endif -%}
  <noscript>
    <img src="{{ image | img_url: '720x' }}" alt="{{ image.alt | strip_html | escape }}" class="responsive-wide-image"/>
  </noscript>
</div>
